<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12059a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12059a">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12059a"> 59(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> S.P waterworship</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[SP and the Druid]</font> King Laogaire now interposed, and commanded each of the disputants to cast his book into the water, promising that he would adhere to the religion of him whose book should escape uninjured. St. Patrick said to the King, &lsquo;I shall obey your wish,&rsquo; but the Druid declined to submit to the judgment, on the pretext that the Saint paid Divine worship to water, because he knew that St. Patrick made men Christians by the water of baptism. <small> William Canon Fleming, <a name="WFSP" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#WFSP"><cite title="source">The Life of St Patrick: Apostle of Ireland</cite></a> (1905) 97</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
